{"/service/ndnp/nmu/batch_nmu_dumas_ver01/data/sn84031081/00415627828/1921031101/0674.xml":{"full_text":"Albuquerque Morning Journal, Friday, March 11,1921\n1EI11EGI\nTO U CdilESS\nTOfllQjpP\nMore Adequate Provision to\nBe Requested For Ex\nService Men, Commander\nj Informs Harding.\n(Ily The Ao'in(i-a Tress.)\n.Washington. March 10. Tho\nAmerican legion's legislative pro\ngram for the special si'sniim of eon\npress wan outlined today to Presi\ndent Harding by F. W. Galbraith,\nJr, national commander of the le\nsion, who said that the president\nwas Impressed by the necessity of\nmaUing more adequate provision\nfor war veterans, especially dis\nabled men.\nMr. Galhrnith expressed the be\nlief that the administration would\ngive whole hearted support to the\nregion's plans. Which include pro\nvlsion,for the grouping of all gov\nernment soldier relief agencies into\nono bureau and a continuous hos\npital building program.\nThe legion, he said, also will ask\nthat veterans receiving vocational\ntraining be given adequate compen\nsation. The matter of securing the re\nturn of Grover C. Tiergdoll. draft\nevader, now in Germany, was ii.it\ndiscussed with the president, Mr.\nGalbraith said. At the \"proper\ntime,\" however, ho added, the\nquestion would he brought to the\nattention of the administration.\nAmerican legion posts, he said,\nshortly will start a movement to\nget the slacker back.\n\"He's one Eocho we want,\" he\nbald.\nWORKINGMEN'S\nt COMPENSATION\nACT IS PASSED\n(Continued from Pag On.)\nfligent, students at Btato expense.\nThis bill ia one of the \"old reli\nables'\" introduced at every session.\nIt has heretofore died in the senate.\nIt would also appear that the dis\ntrict courts of the Sunshine state\nwill have to forego \"phonographic\nreporters\" as house bill IS. pro\nviding such, is still deep in the\nhouse committee. The streams of\nthe state may go ungauged for the,\nnext two years unless house bill 3\",\nappropriating 15,000 for this pur\npose, is succored during the final\ndays. It Is In the house committee\nwith about eighty other bills, in\ncluding one telling how blind elect\nors shall vote; one providing an an\nnual penson of 5500 for teachers\nwho have served twenty years in\nthe public schools; one creating a\nboard of examiners for auto me\nchanics; another for traveling\ncourt reporters, doubtless designed\nto supplement tho \"phonographic\"\nreporters; the bill limiting the\nlength of trains, and one prohibit\ning the introduction of insect nests.\nI5ao l$osiiir HIIIk.\nTiills in the house are now being\ntaken up at' tho pleasure of the\nsteering committee and largely\nupon the motion of It. Ij. Baca of\nSanta Fe, chairman of this com\nmlitee. There arc eishty house\nbills in the hands of the steering\ncommittee. NiiK'teen of the tWen-ty-tiine\nbills introduced i\" the\nhouse since last Friday have been\nI passed by tile house and the indi\ncations are ui.il nil ftf lan1 em.- aie\nmore certain to receive action than\nthose introduced earlier in the ses\nsion. In addition to th there\nare forty-eight senate bills before\nthe house and ill the hands of the\nsteering commit ti e. The order in\nwhich they are tal;eu op will de\npend largely upon the persuasive\npowers the introducers and per\nsons interested in their passage are\nable to exercise upon the h.nise\nsteering committee, particularly\nthe chairman. At this sta;:e of the\ngame \"trades\" are the 'order when\nthe stwitig committees of both\nhouses bokt lip bills in order to\nbring the other\" to Mra.fi and force\nthe final passage of their respective\nbills. '\"'V,'\nDemocrats Complain.'\nDemocrats In the house com\nplained today that the republican\nmajority Is rushing through bills\nthat are not yet printed and that\nthe members are not informed I\nabout.\nThus was passed house bill 3 2 S,\nintroduced yesterday afternoon,\nand passed last night and which\nprovides that the governor may ap\npoint a temporary successor to\nSecretary Fall and then call a spe\ncial election to fill the vacuncy in\nthe senate. But the bill does not\nprovide when the special election\nis to be called apparently making\nit optional at any timo during the\nunexpired term.\nWhat JIoiiho Did.\nThe house last night passed six\nteen bills and killed six. The bill\nproviding for employment of ste\nnographers for district attorneys\nand that licensing dunce halls were\ntabled.\nThe bill by Itnea preserving the\npurity of elections, was passed.\nThirty miles an hour is the maxi\nmum speed for motor cars In the\nstate, according to the provisions\nof another house bill which was\npassed.\nThe house also passed house bill\n324, which would enabl i counties\nto pay election expenses,\nMAY POSTPONE SOUTH\nPARLIAMENT IN ERIN\n(By Tho Amoclslfd Frc.)\nLondon, March 1 0.- Answering\na (iest Ion In the house of commons\ntoday, Premier Lloyd George de\nclared he had received a resolution\npassed at a meeting of the south\nern unionists In Dublin asking\npostponement of tho appointed day\nfor the setting up of the southern\nparliament. He said that the gov\nernment would consider the request\nbut that there would be no post\nponement In the case of the north\nern parliament. He denied that\n300 military blockhouses were be\ning erected around tho northern\ncounties-\n100 PRESENT AT\n'DIH GIVEN BY\nSOLDIEpKGUE\nDisabled Soldiers and Guests\nHear Addresses and Fine\nMusical Program; War\nMothers Dedicate Flag\nA truly representative patriotic\nand civil group was gathered to\ngether at the Y. W. C. A. lust night\nwhere places for one hundred\nguests were laid at the. banquet\ngiven by the local post of the na\ntional. Disabled Soldiers' league.\nFollowing an excellent dinner, over\nwhich Post Commander W. A.\nCovey presided rtR toastmastej, a\nprayer was offered by the Hev. C.\n(i. I.'eckman, dedicating the flag\nwhich had been presented to the\npost by the War Mothers.\nFather D. P, Dawton, S. X, then\nrecited a poem composed especially\nfor the occasion and entitled\n\"Memories.\" District Attorney E.\nI'. Garcia gave an Interesting ad\ndress on \"Morale and the. Constitu\ntion,\" beginning with the revolu\ntionary spirit and going on through\nthe Spanish-American war, cul\nminating in the recent victory In\nFrance.\nMiss Eleanor Lynch played two\nviolin solos, and short addresses\nwere made by representatives of\ntho War Mothers, Mrs. Belle Nye\nand Mrs. William McClurken. Miss\nIrma Wcgs, followed with a piano\nsolo, and F. O. Wosterfiold, post\ncommander of the American legion,\nwas then called upon by the toast\nmaster. J. R. Whitesides spoke for\nthe Veterans of Foreign Wars and\nField Secretary Evans for the Red\nCross.\nThe thanks of the post were ex\npressed to the V. W. C. A. and an\nannouncement was made for the\nnext rehearsal of tho minstrel show\nwhich is called for Saturday night\nat 7 6'clock at the Albuquerque\nISnsiness college- Various civic and\npatriotic organizations have en\ndorsed the minstrels which will be\ngiven about two weeks after that\ngiven by tho Elks in April.\nFather D. P. Lawton was ap\npointed chaplain of the Disabled\nSoldiers' league. He Is already\nchaplain of the Veterans of tha\nSpanish-American war. It was an\nnounced that the disabled soldiers,\n150 strong, would accompany the\nWar Mothers on foot and in auto\nmobiles, to their tree planting cer\nemony on Sunday, March 20.\nEXHIBITION GAMES\n1\nNationals, 7; Association, (5.\nCrowley, La., March 10. Exhi\nbition: Score: XI. 11. F.\nSt. Louis National 7 10 3\nIndianapolis, American As\nsociation S 8 1\nHa'tt'eVlr-s:'- Doil'fon, Sells and Eif-\nfert; Partlelt, E'tUing Cavet and\nGoRsett.\nI Instant\nTftSTUM\nA EVFffAOC\nInstant\nPOSTUM\na table drink, of delightful\nflavor, healthful and satisfying\nMade at the table, a cup at\na time, strong or mild, to\nsuit the individual taste\n\"There's a Season 'for Postum\nSOLD BY GROCERS EVERYWHERE\n1, w.\nI ,,;v;5l'\n\n6 i\n\"IF ITS HARDWARE Wt rlAvc li\nt'irtt and Copper Pnont 74\nU IS\nNl\nLESLIE GILLETT\nAGAIN SELECTED\nSTATE ENGINEER\n(By Staff Correspondent.)\nSanta Fe. March 10. Governor\nMechem today announced the se\nlection of Leslie A. Glllett as state\nengineer for a term of two years,\nJames B. Read as banking exam\niner for a term of two years, and\nW. W. Rlsdon as state mining in\nspector for a similar term. All\nthree are now serving in these\npositions, having been appointed\nby the previous governor.\nThe governor also announced the\nnomination of Mrs. C. D. Parsons\nof Chaves county. Walter Mays of\nSocorro county and C. II. Conner\nof Pernnllllo county as members\nof the suite board of osteopathy.\nHe revised his list of members of\nthe state board of education and\nprescribed the terms for which the\nmembers were to be appointed.\nThe new list stands: J. W. Willson,\nRoswell. for a term of two years;\nHenito Baca, Ils Vegas, two years;\nMrs. Josie D. iockhart. Raton, four\nyears: E. L. Enloe, .Socorro, four\nyears, and Oliver M. Lee, Alamo\ngordo, four years.\nThe governor still must appoint\nthe warden of the state peniten\ntiary, the regents of the Las Vegas\nnormal and the members of the\ndepartment of public welfare.\nBURNS AND PINEAU TO\nMEET AGAIN IN MAIN\nMATCH MONDAY NIGHT\nWrestling fans will have another\nopportunity of seeing Frank Burn,\nveteran wrestler, in action again\non Monday night when he meets\ntieorce Plneati at Moose hall in tno\nmain event of what promises to bo\nan all-star card. Burns lost a\nhandicap match to Flneau and\nYoung Savage here sometime ago.\nHe was contracted to throw each\nof these men In one hour. Savage\nwas disposed of in twenty-eight\nminutes, but he failed to make\ngood on Fineau's end of tho deal.\nSince leaving the city after tho\nhandicap bout, Burns Is said to\nhave been taking part in one or\ntwo matches each week with sotno\nof the speediest grapplors of tno\nwest and northwest. Reports from\ncities which have seen his last few\nmatches are very favorable and\nindicate that the veteran Is not on\nly keeping his ewn. but adding to\nhis skill.\nAlthough th preliminaries have\nnot yet been completely arranged,\nthey are expected to bring out some\ngood matches. An effort Is being\nmade to find a man to grapple with\nSavage, who proved his worth at\ntho mat game by staying with\nPlneau for fifty-one minutes In\ntheir match ut Moose hall a few\nnights ago.\nS. V. Trains on Time for Two Weeks\nDuring the last two weeks none\nof the five Santa Fe transcontl\nnental trains running from Chicago\nto California was even a minute\nlate thouirh they traversed a dis\ntance more than seven times\naround the world, that ia a total of\n182.219 miles. With one exception\nSanta Fe daily trams arrived on\nthe dot and from February 5 to\nMarch 3. inclusive, all through\ntrains arrived on time.\nMan Disfigured at Planing Mill.\nWilliam Bentley, .American Lum\nber company planing mill employe,\nwas scraping a revolver belt with\na knife Tuesday afternoon when\nthe knife flew out of his hand and\nstruck him across the mouth,\nknocking out two of his teeth and\nprobably disfiguring him for life\nby the blow;\nFor Colds, Grip or Influenza\nand as a Preventive, take GROVE'S\nLaxative BROMO QUININE Tab\nlets. The genuine bears the signa\nture ot E. W. Grove. (Be sure you\nget BROMO.) 30c.\nJournal Want Ada. Brine Result.\nAPPROPRIATION\nOF U.N. M.MAY\nBE INCREASED\n(BY H. P. MU.KFS.)\n'a.nta Fe. March 10. Ap\npropriation of the University\nof New Mexico has been raised\nfrom $05,000 to $100,000 by\nthe house finance Committee,\nwhich is revising I ho amended\nsenate appropriation bill No.\n116. President David Spence\nHill and A. A. Sedillo of Albu\n(lueiyiue, a member of, the\nboard of regents, appeared\nbefore the house committee\nthis morning and pleaded the\nease. of the university.\nIt is expected that the sen\nate will not accept the house\namendments increasing the\nappropriations and that the\nbill will then be referred to\nconference committees of the I\ntwo houses for readjustment. j\nAppropriations, particularly\nof the educational institutions, j\nare being raised generally, j\nmembers of the house finance\ncommittee admitted this after\nnoon. One member estimated\nabout $7,500 had been add\nto the senate figures which in\ncreased the total of the origi\nnal bill about $100,000.\nThe house committee Is\nmeeting tonight to complete\nconsideration of the bill and it\nIs expected to be taken up at\nthe session of the house to\nmorrow morning.\nSTRIKE VOTE TO BE\nSUBMITTED TO THE\nPACKERS' EMPLOYES\n(Continued from Page One.)\ncils were Instructed to take no\naction in calling a strike until au\nthorized to do so by the board. No\nmore delay than \"a sensible hand\nling of the situation requires,\" was\nasked In taking the referendum\nand putting the result into effect.\nInjunction Proceedings.\nProposed Injunction proceedings\nto restrain the packers from put\nting into effect their wage and hour\nchange orders which, the employes\ncontend, constitute a violation of\nthe war-time agreement, were out\nlined In conference today. The.\nmatter was referred to the ex\necutive board for action, which will\nbe determined after further con\nferences with Redmond S. Brennan,\nthe union's general counsel.\nThe situation in Kansas, where\nthe state industrial law requires a\nthirty-day notice for such wage and\nworking conditions notices, was al\nso discussed. Delegates maintain\ned that the Kansas law had not\nbeen complied with.\nArrangements for mass meetings\nand a camnaiEn for membership\nwere urged in other resolutions I\nadopted by tho conference. 'It was\nannounced that a mas-s meeting\nwould he held in East St. Louis,\n111., Saturday, and one in Chicago\non Sunday-\nBUSINESS SLIP\n101\nPREVAILS A\nNATION'S M FAT SI PPI.Y\nNOT TO BK lXTKKKl'ITKD\nChicago, March 10. Assurances\nthat the nation's meat supply will\nnot be interrupted, regardless ot\nany action taken by the unidns on\nthe recently announced redwotlon\nof wages and readjustment of\nworking hours, was given today by\nthe packers.\n\"Despite tho striko threats being\nmade by the agents of the unions,\nwe do not expect any trouble that,\nwill interfere with the nation's\nmeat supply,\" said a statement\nfrom Armour Co. \"A survey of\nthe packing plants indicates that\nthe individual employes understand\nthe situation and do not want to be\nforced into idleness or to bo-asked\nto go on strike wh?n there are\nthousands of unemployed men who\nare eager for packing house jobs,\neven at the reduced pay. The\nunion leaders who are talking\nstrike do not represent 25 per cent\nof the packing plants' employes.\n\"The nation is engaged in ati ef\nfort to get back to normal, which\nin the main means deflation of\nprices. Those who are talking\nstrike to uphold inflated war-time\nwages are obstructing the nation's\nreturn to normal. We stand with\nthe public in tho fight against war\nprices in time of peace.\"\nA. F. OF U SF.C'RFTAItY\nPK K8KNTH M EM Mi.WDl'M\nWashington. March 10. The po\nsition of the packing house em\nployes as regards the wage reduc\ntions announced by the packers\nwas embodied in a memorandum\nleft at the White House today by\nFrank Morrison, secretary of the\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nPresident Harding was receiving\nmembers of the diplomatic corps\nand Mr. Morrison left the memo\nrandum with Mr. Harding's secre\ntary, George B. Christian, who said\nhe would call It to the president's\nattention.\nThe president earlier had re\nceived a telegraphic appeal from\nthe meat cutters and butchers\nunions, who asked that he prevent\nwage reductions and changed work\ning conditions becoming effective\nMonday as proposed by their em\nployers. The telegram as a mat\nter of routine, was referred to the\ndepartment of labor.\nREVENUE CODE\nPASSES SENATE\n(Continued from fage On.)\nown beliefs at times in order to\nmako an ad valorem assessment\nafter appraisal possible In the\nfuture.\nPraise For riitlliM.\nSenator Mitchell added a word\nol. appreciation for Phillips' serv\nices and expressed tho hope that\nthe senators would apply tho ad\nvalorem basis to an estimato of\nSellers' talk, which, he declared,\nwould be \"minus nothing.\"\nfeenator Grantham, another dem\nocrat, declared that, an earnest ef\nfort had been put forth on tho part\nof the men who drew the bill.\nHedgcork added that he would\nhave liked to have seen some\nchanges made, but favored th,e\ncode as a whole. Senator Abeyta\ndeclared that the republican ma\njority stood for reason and Justice\nto the welfare of their constituents\nand were in a position to give\neveryone a square deal.\nThe roll call was ordered anT all\nthe Senators, except Sellers, voted\nfor the adoption of the code.\nThe measure provides for a man\ndatory appraisal of mines which\nshall be completed the third\nMonday in February. While \"U dots\nnot establish the ad valorem prin-r\nclple as the only factor. It make\nIts adoption in the future extreme\nly probable. .L-L'i\nJATIOpiSO\nDepression Continues in Eu\nrope, Except in Italy; Ex\nports and Imports De\ncrease in England.\n(By The Annorlutcrf rrws.)\nWashington, March 10. Contin\nued business depression in Europe,\nexcept Italy, was reported by Am\nerican consuls in the monthly ca\nble survey of world economic con\nditions issued today by the depart\nment of commerce. Signs of Im\nprovement were seen in tho Far\nEast, but little change was noted\nin the South American countries.\nBoth exports and Imports are de\ncreasing in Great Britain, the sur\nvey said, increasing unemployment.\nPayment of heavy taxes was re\ngarded as a cause of the lightness\nin the money market and English\nbanks were said to have loaned\ntwo-thirds of their resources to pri\nvate enterprises,\nBanks' Credit Strained.\nRecent, price declines and busi\nness stagnation in France, accord\ning to the survey, have tended to\nstrain the credit of banks. A liqui\ndation of the. government-owned\nmerchant fleet, aggregating 1.000,\n000 gross tons, Is being urged.\nItalian banks are reporting large\nnroflts. however, the survey con\ntinued, and the condition of the\ngovernment finances was regarded\nas more favorable. laical unrest\nand strikes about Rome are de\ncreasing, but unemployment Is in\nevidence, it added.\nGerman interests are attempting\nto obtain control of the Austrian\ngovernment's former ammunition\nplants, the survey reported, and\nGerman capital is, trying to control\nthe Iron industry in Austria. Tho\nGeneral condition of the Austrian\ngovernment finances was regarded\nas more unfavorable. Tho cost of\nliving there rose 10 per cent In\nFebruary, It was, reported.\nGerman Competition.\nBusiness depression Is increasing\nin the Scandinavian countries, the\nsurvey asserted, while German\ncompetition is placing many indus\ntries In a worse condition than\nformerly.\nJapan's foreign trade continued\nthe increase started in January, ac\ncording to the survey, while bank\nloans increased under lower rates\nand easier money. An upward\ntrend In tho exchange rate on the\nUnited States it was said, is looked\nfor in Japan. Orders for foreign\ngoods are decreasing in China, but\nthe trade depression is expected\nto improve by July, while the fi\nnancial situation Is Improving.\nTHREE EDUCATION\nBOARD MEMBERS TO\nBE ELECTED SOON\n(By Staff CoiTcspond-ent.)\nSanta Fe. March 10. Three\nmembers of board of education\nshould bo elected this April, ac\ncording to a decision of Harry S\nBowman, attorney-general ot the\nstate.\nMr. Bowman holds that section\n4871 of the code of 1915. provided\nthat on the first Tuesday in April\n1915. the towns and villages should\nelect two members of the board of\neducation and on the first Tuesday\nin Aorll. 1917. should elect three\nmembers, and thereafter a regular\nnlectinn for members should be\nheld on the first Tuesday in April\nof each odd numbered year to\nelect members succeeding those\nwhose terms expire, provided that\nin towns incorporated under spe\ncial acts, the election should be the\nsecond Tuesday in April. This\nwould bring about the election of\nthreo members this year,\nPRINCESS HELENE\nOF GREECE WEDS\nRUMANIAN PRINCE\nlllr Thn Auorlnted Prma.)\nLondon, March 10. The wedding\nof Princess Heleno of Greece ana\nCrown Prince Carol of Rumania,\ntook place today in the cathedral\nIn Athens, says a dispatch to the\nCentral News. The cathedral was\ncrowded with relatives, members of\nthe cabinet, diplomatic, civil repre\nsentatlves and officers of the army\nand navy.\nAfter the ceremony a, salute was\nfired by tne guns in tne fortresses\nand church hells were rung. State\ncarriages conveyed the bride and\ngroom and their relatives and\nguests through decorated streets to\nthe palace where a reception was\nheld.\nMOTHER!\n\"California Syrup of Figs'\nChild's Best Laxative\nAccept \"California\" Syrup of\nFigs only look for the name Cali\nfornia on the package, then you are\nlure your chilti ia having the best\nand most harmless physic for the\nlittle stomach, liver and bowels\nChildren love Its fruity taste. Full\ndirections on each bottle. You\nBiava AUTO Store\nGallup, N.M.\nStmlcbaker Automobile and\nParts, and Aceseories.\nflLIEillOF\nBIG TRACTS IN\nElAi IS\nOwners of Huge Estates Are\nCompelled to Give Them\nUp So They Can Be Sold\nto Small Farmers.\n(Ilj- The AMcIuled From.)\nDublin, March lo. The Dull\nEireann's department of agricul\nture is dealing with what is re\ngarded an tho most important work\nof the Irish republican government\nthe alienation of land from the\nbig estates of landlords and its dis\ntribution among\" smail farmers, who\nhave not enough land to earn a\nliving.\nSince last April when there was\na revival of the \"Land War\" which\nhas occupied such a conspicuous\nplace in Ireland's history, the\nDail's so-called \"land judges\" have\ndealt with 229 cases, involving\nabout 50. 000 Irish acres. An Irish\nacre is a third again as largo as\nan American acre.\nin eighty-three of these cases\n20.X75 acres were \"alienated,\" that\nis, taken by decree from big estates\nand sold to small farmers who\nwere able to prove that they did\nnot possess sufficient land to pro\nvido' a living for themselves and\nfamilies. In sixty-seven cases\njudgment was given against the\n\"claimant,\" the farmer, in favor of\nthe \"resister.\" the landlord with a\nbig estate.\nLandlords Anxious.\nMore than 100 cases are pend\ning, most of them in Roscommon,\nwhich is in a highly disturbed\nstate., If tho land judges are hot\npermitted to deal with these cases,\nSinn Fein fears another upheaval\nin the spring. Landlords in the\ndistricts affected are said to view\nthe situation with great anxiety.\nThe land question has been quite\nacute in Ireland for hundreds of\nyears. It arose when the first\nIrishmen were driven in feudal\ntimes from their ancient clan lands.\nTho great war In the last century\ncleared off the landlords and then\nthe British government set up the\ncongested districts board.\nKevin R. O'Shiel, a land judge:\ntold the correspondent that the\nwilful and incredible slowness of\ntho board Is the principal cause of\ntho present agitation. \"In Ron-\ncommon alone it is the landlord of\n60,000 acrea of excellent, unten\nanted land and It is the lord of\niliany thousands of acres, all un\ntenanted, in Galway, Mayo, Clare\nand other counties,\" he said.\n\"Theso estates are capable of sup\nporting at least 250,000 people and\nthere are many valuable ranches\nlying derelict in parts of tho coun\ntry where there is Berious conges\ntlqn.'\"\nTho Dail Eireann, he said, \"is\nmerely carrying out the work\nwhich the congested districts board\nneglected.\"\nArbitration, Courts.\n\"Arbitration courts,\" he contin\nued, \"have been a revelation of ef\nficiency and dispatch. Now that\nthe way has been made clear the\nsolution of tho land question is\nonly a matter of time.\"\nThe landlords themselves, who\nare mostly unionists, welcome the\nwork of the land courts, according\nto Mr. O'Shiel. He said that after\nthe shooting to death last spring of\nthe Galway landlord, Captain\nShaw-Taylor, landlords made earn-\nf\nComes\n,tO,!Ycii\nIf you are careful to follow\nthe advice of your older, friends or\nrelatives. For over 50 years ago, Dr.\nPierce, then a young practicing physician\ndiscovered that a prescription made up of\nLady-slipper root, Viburnum, black and\nblue Cohcfeh, Unicom root, Oregon Grape\nroot, and made into a liquid extract, or\ntablets, wflth'out alcohol, was. wonderfully\nenicient as a tonic lor those pains and T\nills so corrnmon among the women, folks.\nxnis woman s ionic nas soia as ur. nerce s favorite Pre\nscription for over fifty years and is just as popular and;\npflFiriftnr. unw as af. anv timp flvpr a millinn hnttloo num\nsold last year and many of your friends and neighbors\ncan testify as to how good it is.\nHartford, Ark. \"I am happy to say that Dr. Pierce's\nFavorite Prescription has done me more good than, any\nthing I have ever taken so far. I was down and out,, but\nnow I feel like a new woman. I was in such shape I\nhated everybody and myself too. When I began taking\nthe Prescription I only weighed 110 pounds but now I\nweigh. 145 and can truthfully say that I believe Dr.\nPierce's Prescription will help any run-down woman if\nshe will give it a trial, for it surely did help me.\" MRS.\nSTELLAR fcALY, Box 243.\nout appeals to Dail Eireann to in\ntervene. According to Mr. O'Shiel, peas\nant farmers witli large families\nfind themselves unable to support\nthem on the meager Income from\ntheir small holdings. They are\nmade) desperate when they are. un\nable to purchase a few additional\nacres from nearby estates which\nare lying idle or used only for\ngrazing.\n\"It is only with such cases that\nwe deal,\" he said. \"The burden of\nproof that his holding is unecono\nmic Is on tho claimant. We do not\ntouch :ases concerning historic\nclaims to land through eviction.\"\nI